    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "There are a few possible answers:\r\n\r\n- If you use Geth to broadcast your transactions, Geth will cache all locally created tx and will try to push them back into the network from time to time (when new peer connections are made).\r\n- Etherscan and Infura AFAIK use custom transaction caching and rebroadcasting, so it also might come from them.\r\n\r\nAll in all once a transaction is signed, there's a non-zero chance that someone will keep it around even if it's not executable yet (out of balance) and submit it later. Also each client implementation behaves differently wrt tx pooling, so it can also happen that even though Geth drops it, Besu or some other clients keeps it and republishes it.",
